<br>
The main issue with DUI's nowadays are not the &quot;Someone was an idiot once&quot; crowd.  The main issue are the serious repeat offenders.  The ones that are caghut literally dozens of times.  A lot of them have already spent years in jail, can never have a drivers licsense again, and still not only do they still drive, they continue to drink(and usually way beyond just impaired) and drive.  Nothing seems to stop them.(and shaming isn't going to work on them either, most are allready motorious in there localities.<br>
<br>
One judge got so frustrated with one guy, his sentence was for the guy to move within walking distance of a bar.  The Judge got flamed all to hell for being &quot;leinient&quot; but when he explained his reasoning it made sense.  This guy had already permenently lost his liscence, had already spent years in jail and nothing stopped him from getting behind the wheel plastered out of his mind.   The judge was less concearned about punishing the guy (which wasn't working and was not maiking the streets any safer) and more concearned with trying to keep him off the road.<br>
<br>
It is because of guys like the above that I think the latest push to lower the blood alchol limit in my mind was both misguided and stupid.  It will do almost nothing to make the roads safer and is the reason a LOT of states resisted it till the Federal Government forced it down thier throats.  The problems are these hard core drunk drivers.  These people don't stop drive at .09 %  they are driveing around with .29%.<br>
<br>
While I don't think someone who has a .08 blood alchol level should be driveing, they are not in reality any worse <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>at that point</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than someone who is sleep deprived or is distracted(talking on a cell phone, eating lunch while driveing etc.)  <br>
<br>
On another front, at the beareucratic level, DUI laws have often been shamefully hijacked to become a revenue genertion scheme instead of a public safety issue.  Changes to the laws(and regulations) are often meant to squeaze more money out instead of actually trying to stop or reduce the problem.  While there is nothing wrong with a drunk driver paying through the nose(it is a crime after all), but the goal should be for drunk driving to stop, not to use them as a revenue source.<br>
<br>
At one point here in Ohio one of our judges had to take the BMV to court over this issue.  He won, but still it is common for Judges to have to arm twist the BMV over DUI cases.  (These usually involve acquitall or convictions on lessor charges, but the BMV was still treating the case like a DUI because the fines and &quot;administrative costs) were so much higher.<br>
<br>
The sad fact is, I think we pretty much reached the limit of what punishment and laws can do to the &quot;casual&quot; drunk driver to get them to stop or not do it in the first place.  Adding any more won't reduce it much (though it will punish those who do more). <p><center><font face="lucida handwriting, arial" color="006800" size=+2><b>Radgen Waldjaeger</font></b><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="675f00" size=+1><b>Semi-retired Outrider of Karana</font><br><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/tiger_run_md_clr.gif></center>
